context: The French crown's increasing dominance over the Papacy culminated in the transference of the Holy See to <a1_0><b6_0>Avignon<b6_0/><a1_0/> in 1309. When the Pope returned to Rome in <a2_0><b7_0>1377<b7_0/><a2_0/>, this led to the election of different popes in Avignon and Rome, resulting in the <a0_0><b5_0>Papal Schism<b5_0/><a0_0/> (<a3_0><b8_0>1378–1417<b8_0/><a3_0/>). The Schism divided Europe along political lines; while <a4_0><b9_0>France, her ally Scotland and the Spanish kingdoms<b9_0/><a4_0/> supported the Avignon Papacy, France's enemy England stood behind the Pope in Rome, together with Portugal, Scandinavia and most of the German princes.
